{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_kale_ver01/data/2017236974/00279558078/1945092701/0872.xml":{"full_text":"t\nMany Workers Do Not Know Rights\nUnder Unemployment Insurance Law\n1 mo lo unc m\nseries of articles on the role of\nunemployment insurance during\nreconversion. The first article\nshows how as much as $603,000\ncould be returned to Halifax\nCounty\u2019s stream of commerce by\nunemployment insurance over a\n4-months period, if a 40 percent\nlay-off of workers took place.)\nMany workers who may benefit\nfrom North Carolina\u2019s unemploy\nment insurance law, do not know\ntheir rights under this program.\nSome do not know how to apply\nfor benefits and others have seri\nous misconceptions of the law. Yet\nunemployment insurance can go\nfar to prevent the spread of a\nwave of \"fear psycholgy\u201d that\ncould paralyze essential spending\n\u25a0during the crucial gap between\nfull war production and full peace\nproduction.\nInasmuch as the program is de\nsigned to tide workers over the\nperiod between jobs, and to main\n4 i :i:4-V.^\nVCtlili OUOUU/OO\ncommunity, it must be widely un\nderstood if it is to function prop\nerly. The Herald has secured from\nthe Unemployment Compensation\nCommission the results of a spec\nial survey made to determine com\nmon misconceptions of North\nCarolina\u2019s unemployment insurance\nlaw, and it presents these here, to\ngether with the correct facts. Many\npeople think that: (1) \u201cUnemploy\nment insurance is retroactive. A\nworker can collect benefits for the\nweeks he was out of work before\nhe filed his claim.\u201d\nWrong. If a worker fails to\nfile his claim for benefits as soon\nas he loses his job, he may lose\nbenefits. His claim isn't acted\nupon until he has filed it at the\nnearest State unemployment insur\nance office. He should file a claim\nthe very day he is laid off, or the\nnext morning.\n(2) \u201cAn unemployed worker has\nto wait a week before getting any\nunemployment insurance.\u201d\nRight, but his waiting period\ndoesn\u2019t start until he has filed his\nclaim. He should not make the\nmistake of waiting at home for\na week and then filing it.\n(3) \"If a worker quits his job\nbecause he expects to be laid off\nanyhow, he can still collect un\nemployment compensation.\u201d\nWrong. If he quits without some\ngood cause connected with the job\nhis benefit checks will be held up\nfor several extra weeks.\n(4) \"A worker can collect unem\nployment insurance when he is\nsick.\u201d\nWrong. Rhode Island is the only\nState that provides for sickness\nmemp\u2019oyment. In North Carolina,\n10 such arrangement is provided\nby law. In order to collect unem\nployment benefits, a worker must\nbe able to work and looking for\nwork. If he is sick, he is obviously\nnot \"able\u201d to work.\n(5) \u201cI paid for unemployment\ninsurance with the one percent\nsocial security tax they deducted\nfrom my pay. Why can\u2019t I collect\nit automatically?\u201d\nWrong. That one percent tax\nwas for old-age and survivors* in\nsurance, not unemployment insur\nance. Taxes for unemployment\ncompensation in North Carolina\nare paid by employers, and the\nlaw caretully ciennes me ruies wr\npayment of benefits to unemploy\ned workers.\n(6) \"I'm not going to file a\nclaim for unemployment compen\nsation until I need it, because it\u2019s\na form of charity.\u201d\nWrong. This notion is a hang\nover from the days of relief. Un\nemployment insurance is NOT\ncharity and never was. It comes\nto workers as a matter of right,\nif they qualify for it by their\nwork records. Their unemployment\ninsurance payments are based on\nhow long they worked and how\nmuch they earned, not on whether\nthey need the money.\n(7) \"Unemployment insurance\nencourages idleness it\u2019s a vaca\ntion at Government expense.\u201d\nWrong. The law does not allow\nanyone to collect unemployment\ncompensation unless he is looking\nfor work which he cannot find,\nand registers each week at a pub\nlic employment office. Moreover,\nthe funds for his benefits do not\ncome from general Government\nrevenue, hut from a special unem\nployment insurance trust fund,\nraised through taxes on employers\nof the insured workers.\n(8) \u201cEverybody gets $20 a, week\nfor 16 weeks in unemployment\nbenefits.\u201d\nWrong. Benefit checks amount\nto from $4 to $20 a week. They are\npaid out for anywhere from one\nto 16 weeks. The amount of the\ncheck depends upon the wages\nearned in jobs covered by the\nlaw. The number of weeks depends\non ho wlong the claimant is out\nof a job.\n(9) \u201cUnemployment insurance is\na burden on the community.\u201d\nWrong. During periods of tem\nporary unemployment, this insur\nance greatly eases the burdens on\nciky and State government, for it\ncurtails the need for relief meas\nures. It protects individuals, leav\ning community leaders free tr\ntackle broader social issues and\nprepare programs that will create\nemployment again.\nLargest Trust Fund:\nNorth Carolina has an unemploy\nment msuranue iuxiu ui .piud.wu.vw\nto help tide its workers through\neconomic readjustments. In Hali\nfax County, approximately 6,734\nworkers have been holding jobs\ncovered by unemployment insur\nance. If they are laid off, their\n1 benefit payments would probably\naverage about $12.00 a week, for\nas many weeks as they are out\nof work, but not more than 16.\nTo get the \u2018\u2018human side\u201d of re\nconversion, the Herald interview\n1 ed several claimants for unemploy\nment insurance. The largest num\nbers of those recently collecting\npayments (82) percent) have been\nwomen.\nMrs. B. has a son in the service\nand a daughter in the WACS. Her\nhusband still holds his former\npeacetime job, and his wages\nhaven\u2019t gone up though living costs\nhave risen. Mrs. B. never worked\nbefore the war began but wanted\nto do her part in the war effort,\nand help meet the increased living\ncosts, so she took a job in a plant\non war work. The work was not\nphysically difficult, and the pay,\nwith overtime, was about $35.00\nweek. She worked steadily for over\ntwo years and was recently laid\noff. She has tried to find another\njob, for she wants to continue\nworking, but has been unable to\nobtain anything she can do. \u201cWe\u2019d\nbe able to scrape along without\nunemployment insurance,\u201d she said\n\u201cbecause I\u2019ve put quite a bit into\nwar bonds and we could cash them.\nBut we haven\u2019t had to, with my\nbenefit checks of $17.50 a week\ncoming in. It\u2019s been a real help,\nand leaves us with more security\nfor later.\u201d\nMrs. W. said she would have\nbeen hard hit if it hadn\u2019t been for\nunemployment insurance. She has\n.five children, all of school age,\nand she and her husband recently\nI put all their savings into the pur\nchase of a house. When the lay\noff came, both Mr. and Mrs. W.\nlost their jobs, and the $14.00\nchecks each received kept them\nfrom becoming panicky or cashing\nin the children\u2019s war bonds during\nthe few weeks before Mr. W. was\ncalled back to his job. Mrs. W. re\nceived checks for seven weeks and\nthen found a job in a grocery\nstore at a much lower wage.\nThat's the way the stories run.\nFor many workers, tms win oe i,:ie\nfirst time they have been eligible\nfor unemployment insurance bene\nfits, since many of them never\nworked in covered jobs before the\nwar. Tile procedure for collecting\nunemployment benefits is simple,\nand the Unemployment Compensa\ntion Commission has developed a\nstreamlined plan that can be put\ninto effect immediately, when mass\nlay-offs occur.\nGetting Unemployment Benefits:\n(1) When a lay-off comes, go to\nthe nearest employment office,\nregister for work, and file a claim\nfor unemployment insurance\npromptly.\n(2) If you find only part-time\nwork, you may be eligible for par\ntial benefits. Example: Weekly\nbenefits amount $15. Actual earn\nings $10; partial benefit payment\n$7.\n(3) You are entitled to benef!ts\nif you have recently worked long\nenough in covered employment and\nare now out of a job and willing\nand able to work. \u201cCovered em\nployment\u201d includes most mork .n\nfactories ajid other industries, and\nworkers in business concerns,\nwhomever eight or more workers\nare employed. Domestic and Agri\ncultural workers, government em\nployees, and workers for non-prof\nit organizations are not covered.\n(4) If you refuse to take a job\nthat the Unemployment Compen\nsation Commission considers suit- I\nable, you may have to wa,it several\nextra weeks for benefits. Don\u2019t\nrefuse to be interviewed for a\njob, even if you think it is one\nyou will not accept. Instead, go\nand find out the facts. Whether or\nnot a job offered is \u201csuitable work\u201d\nis decdied on the merits of each\ncase. The distance of your home\nfrom the job, its effect on your\nhealth, your previous work his\ntory and perhaps family circum\nstances are taken into account in\nmaking ruling on whether refusal\nof a job means loss of benefits.\n(5) If you are refused benefits,\nyou have the right to appeal, but\nyou must act within five days\nafter the Commission\u2019s statement\nof your benefit rights is mailed to\nyou. Go to the local employment\noffice and ask to have your case\nreviewed.\n(6) If you move to another state\nor have worked in another state,\nyou can get benefits from the\nstate in which y\u00abu worked by an\nplying at the nearest employment\njffice. If you move to another\nsown in the same state, transfer\npour claim to the employment of\n!ice in that town.\n(7) If you are a veteran of\nWorld War II, you get special un\n:mployment benefits. Apply *t\nsame local office where civilian\nworkers apply.\n(8) If you are 65 years old or\nnore, you may want to inquire\nibout starting your claim for old\nige benefits.\nMrs. Thomas P. Silk and dau\nghter, Lois Ann, have returned\nlome from New York, where they\nspent the summer, they were ac\njompanied on their return by MLs\nVlary Ann Silk who will sp<\u00ael\nsome time with them.\n\u2019T\u2019\nWilliam\nPenn\nA/AAv^AAvA.A.\u2022 y.\nV. 1\nPint $1-85\nFifth $3\nIMended Whiikey, 86 proof,\n65% grain neutral spirits\n\u2022/\u2022A. t'-S J\u00a9 St;\u2019ti 7./ -A X r\u2018.\nGOODERHAM WORTS LIMITED\nRSOKIA, IttINOIS\nA r-\u00bb-\u00bb Ua\nWomen do you suffer\nSIMPLE i miA\nSue to Loss of Blood-Iron?\nYou girls who suffer from simple\nanemia or who lose so much during\nmonthly periods you feel tired, weak,\n\"dragged out\u201d\u2014this may be due to low\nblood-iron\u2014so try Lydia E. Plnkham s\nTABLETS at once. Ptnkham\u2019s Tablets\nare'one of tbe very best borne ways to\nhelp build up red blood to give more\nstrength and energy\u2014In such cases.\niMnvhflin'R Tablets are one of tne\ngreatest blood-iron tonics you can buy!\nFollow label directions.\nlltiaLPioMam\u2019s TAB!BTS\nOTTIS J. REYNOLDS\nAttorney And Connsellor-at-Law\nRoanoke Rapids, N. CL\nKidd Building\nAnnouncing removal of office;\nTo 915 Roanoke Ave.\nNext to Tickle\u2019s i\u00bbarber Shop\nNew Phone R-6986\nClosed Mondays until 3 P. M.\nDr. E. D. Hcsrfeoyr\nOptometrist\nRoanoke Rapids, N. C.\nBUY THEM TO FIT\nYOU WOULD never\nthink of wearing a hat\nor shoes that didn\u2019t ex\nactly fit your needs. 41\nYour insurance should\nmeasure your individual\nhazards just as accu\nrately! Buy your policies\n\u201cMade to measure\u201d\nnot in a haphazard man\nner from this Hart\nford agency.\nNATIONAL\nLOAN INSURANCE CO.. INC*!\n12 W. Second St. Dial R444-I 8","height":"21700","width":"14492"}}
